TONE & FEEL — POWERFUL, AUTHORITATIVE
━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━━

This is not a consumer app. This is a government command interface.
It should feel like the person using it has real power and real
responsibility. Design decisions must reflect that.

TYPOGRAPHY:
  - Headings are large, heavy, and confident — no thin fonts anywhere
  - Use tight letter-spacing on all caps labels (tracking-widest)
  - Section labels in strict ALL CAPS small text, muted, spaced out
  - Numbers (stats) should be oversized — 48px minimum — they command
    attention. This is a war room, not a form.

COLOR USE:
  - Orange (#F97316) is reserved for power actions only —
    Approve, Save, Primary CTA. Nothing decorative gets orange.
  - Red (#DC2626) is used for Reject, Revoke, Flag — feels final,
    serious. Never soften it with rounded pill shapes.
  - Green (#16A34A) only appears when something is confirmed safe —
    Verified status, Approved badge, Success toast.
  - Everything else is white or #6B7280. No color for color's sake.

SIDEBAR:
  - Slightly lighter than the main background — #111111 — so it
    reads as a distinct command rail, not just negative space
  - Active nav item: full orange left border (3px), text white,
    background rgba(249,115,22,0.08) — feels selected, not just highlighted
  - "ADMIN PANEL" label under logo in strict letter-spacing,
    muted, all caps — establishes the authority level immediately
  - Officer Approvals nav item has a live amber dot badge showing
    pending count — always visible, creates urgency

CARDS & TABLES:
  - Officer approval cards have a LEFT border accent
    (amber for PENDING, green for VERIFIED, red for REJECTED) —
    color-coding makes the stakes immediately obvious
  - Table rows are dense but not cramped — this is a data interface,
    not a marketing page. Information density signals seriousness.
  - Column headers in ALL CAPS, muted, small — the data is the hero
  - Approve button: solid green, full text "✓ APPROVE OFFICER" —
    uppercase, no ambiguity about what this action does
  - Reject button: red outline, "✕ REJECT" — destructive actions
    never look friendly

SPACING & STRUCTURE:
  - Content starts with no decorative hero section — straight into
    data. Admins are not here for onboarding, they have work to do.
  - Use hard horizontal rules (1px, rgba white 0.08) to divide
    sections — not whitespace alone. Structure should feel rigid,
    deliberate, institutional.
  - Stat numbers on overview page have no card wrapper —
    they sit directly on the dark background, raw and exposed.
    This makes them feel like live data, not UI decoration.

MICRO-DETAILS THAT SIGNAL AUTHORITY:
  - Every destructive action (Reject, Revoke, Flag) requires
    a confirmation step — this signals the system takes actions seriously
  - Timestamps are always precise — "12 Apr 2024, 09:41:03 AM"
    not "2 days ago" — government systems log exactly
  - Badge numbers, station codes, CCTNS IDs shown in
    monospace font (font-mono) — they are identifiers, not prose
  - Status badges are rectangular with sharp corners (rounded-sm only),
    not pill-shaped — pills feel playful, rectangles feel official
  - The "Pending Approvals" count in the sidebar never
    disappears until every officer is actioned — it is a persistent
    reminder of administrative duty
  - Top bar shows "ADMIN · MHA · GOVERNMENT OF INDIA" in strict
    small caps on the right — establishes institutional context
    on every single page
